ayments
The option to redeploy capital frequently with shorter-term investments
A wide swath of deals, ranging from small business loans, merchant cash adv=
ances, trade finance, consumer loans,=C2=A0 and more across the US, Canada,=
 and Latin America
With the market near all-time highs, many investors turn to private credit =
because its returns are historically less correlated to public markets, whi=
ch can stabilize a portfolio during a downturn. Percent is the easiest way =
to start investing in private credit, with minimum investments of $500 and =
average deal terms of just 9 months.=C2=A0
Explore Private Credit and grab a $500 bonus on your first investment. [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/4251f75f-f2ce-4de9-a9af-7df80bf7f404?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 110th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Dan here =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s been a busy week. Aside from writing the We=
ekly Dose, my day job is running a company called Create [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/cfa39783-34e2-4588-bd7=
2-5668bec25e56?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I started Create because I th=
ink way too few people take creatine =E2=80=94 something like 2-3% of the p=
opulation. I think that number should be much closer to 100% than 0%. We=E2=
=80=99re starting to make a dent. We now have well over 100K customers and =
have introduced over 50K folks to creatine for the first time.
This week, we announced a $5M Series A led by Unilever Ventures. The goal i=
s triple down on what=E2=80=99s working, launch new creatine-forward produc=
ts, build out a small team, and expand deeper into retail. The Information =
covered the round here [ https://substack.com/redirect/2c4d1020-db11-4ea6-9=
df7-ba76f7348e95?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ].
I want to say thank you for reading Not Boring. Writing the Weekly Dose all=
owed me to not take a salary from Create for a year, re-invest that capital=
 back into growth, and frankly stay sane as I dealt with the ins-and-outs o=
f building a CPG business. As a thank you, you can get 50% off your next or=
der using optimism50 =E2=80=94 now until the end of the weekend (code auto-=
applied at checkout when using link): get 50% off here [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/cfa39783-34e2-4588-bd72-5668bec25e56?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
(1) Exclusive: OpenAI co-founder Sutskever's new safety-focused AI startup =
SSI raises $1 billion [ https://substack.com/redirect/3c9ed354-7a4a-449a-b8=
82-164407969758?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]
Kenrick Cai [ https://substack.com/redirect/3d3b9b85-cb1a-4524-b34b-8f3fdb0=
a5c0d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 Krystal Hu [ https://substack.com/redirect/3fb0fa37-f301-48bc-a21f-098f3d9=
f9e3b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
and Anna Tong [ https://substack.com/redirect/69627ccd-a3fb-4117-8d60-f5c43=
3ebfade?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for Reuters
Safe Superintelligence (SSI), newly co-founded by OpenAI's former chief sci=
entist Ilya Sutskever, has raised $1 billion in cash to help develop safe a=
rtificial intelligence systems that far surpass human capabilities, company=
 executives told Reuters.
There=E2=80=99s that old story about Picasso. Picasso is sitting in a caf=
=C3=A9 and a woman recognizes him and requests a drawing. Picasso obliged, =
quickly creating a small drawing, and then handed it to her. As he did, he =
said, "That will be $10,000." The woman, surprised, asked, "But it only too=
k you a few minutes to draw this!"
Picasso replied, "No, it took me 40 years."
That=E2=80=99s kind of what is happened at Safe Superintelligence (SSI). Th=
e company has no product, a relatively vague roadmap, and just a small team=
 of 10 yet it was able to raise $1B at a reported $5B valuation. But the te=
am didn=E2=80=99t just raise the round overnight =E2=80=94 co-founders Ilya=
 Sutskever, Daniel Gross, and Daniel Levy have been working towards this fo=
r years. Specifically with Ilya at Google and OpenAI and Gross as the found=
er of Cue (acquired by Apple) and one of the most active investors of this =
AI boom.
Safe Superintelligence is the company=E2=80=99s name, mission, and entire p=
roduct roadmap. The company is designed to make a straight-shot at safe sup=
erintelligence, without short-term commercial or product cycle pressures. I=
 guess we=E2=80=99ll have to just wait and see how that strategy plays out.
(2) They Built This Robot For Your Home | 1X Technologies [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/d914f21f-9c7f-43a0-9b89-606e5efa8fcd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From S3
1X Technologies is making humanoid robots for the home. Its latest robot, N=
eo, is apparently ready for mass production and pilots within in the home, =
and will even be available for sale as early as next year.
Neo is unique from other humanoid robots in two major ways. First, Neo is d=
esigned for the home, meaning that it can handle a multitude of different t=
asks and environments within the home. Second, it=E2=80=99s designed for ev=
eryday safe collisions (bumps, swipes, brushes, etc). Humans are constantly=
 safely colliding with and within our environments, but heavy, rigid robots=
 have not traditionally been designed for such collisions. That=E2=80=99s i=
s an issue within the home.
1X has been in this space for over a decade now, and introduced an earlier =
humanoid robot EVE back in 2017. EVE comes with a wheeled base and is alrea=
dy pretty widely used in commercial settings like factories and warehouses.
We=E2=80=99ll see how Neo holds up in the market. Elon has claimed that Opt=
imus will eventually cost $20K and tackle many of the same household use ca=
ses, while Unitree=E2=80=99s G1 already costs just $16K. No matter who wins=
, we continue to be amazed that the question on robots seems to be: =E2=80=
=9Cwho will win and how cheaply can they do it?=E2=80=9D versus =E2=80=9Cwi=
ll these things ever work?=E2=80=9D=20
(3) Can Solar Costs Keep Shrinking? [ https://substack.com/redirect/b6bab83=
9-d990-4034-ae6e-24542cae74f6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Tomas Pueyo for Uncharted Territories
If we want to know whether solar electricity costs will continue shrinking =
in the future, we need to break down its costs and figure out to what exten=
t each one can shrink.
We=E2=80=99ve all been the beneficiaries of one of the most impressive cost=
 curves in history. Since 1975, the price of solar photovoltaic (PV) panels=
 has been shrinking around 12% per year. That decrease in price is, in part=
, the result of a massive increase in solar capacity (ie installs.) Simply =
put, =E2=80=9Cthe more solar panels we produce, the cheaper they get.=E2=80=
=9D
The question is: can we keep it up or have solar costs plateaued? According=
 to Pueyo, there is still some room for cost improvements. First, there is =
no reason to believe that we=E2=80=99ll stop installing more solar panels, =
and in doing so, the cost of solar panels will continue to decline. Second,=
 technological improvements like thinner or more efficient panels should co=
ntinue to drive down costs. And finally, the whole ecosystem around solar s=
hould become more efficient =E2=80=94 everything from the cost of capital t=
o permitting costs =E2=80=94 as solar becomes more ubiquitous and an even m=
ore important component of our energy mix.
Let=E2=80=99s keep driving down that curve until we have solar energy too c=
heap to meter.
(3a) Solar will get too cheap to connect to the power grid [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/7bfb924c-6868-4ff5-9824-50b7f28799ea?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Ben James
The cost of solar panels is plummeting, and this will flood the power grid =
with cheap electricity. But that=E2=80=99s just Act 1. We won=E2=80=99t sto=
p building solar at the limits of the grid - we=E2=80=99ll build a lot more=
=2E
OK, one more bullish solar think piece to share =E2=80=94 this time from Be=
n James. James=E2=80=99 essay takes Pueyo=E2=80=99s argument a few steps fu=
rther: not only will solar continue to get cheaper and cheaper, but it=E2=
=80=99ll be so cheap and abundant that it=E2=80=99ll exceed grid capacity, =
and we=E2=80=99ll have to use off-grid storage and intermittent processes.
James and Pueyo agree that solar costs will continue to plummet. Panels are=
 getting cheaper, which will lead to more installs, which will lead to chea=
per panels, and so on and so forth. The cost curve will keep marching down =
and to the right, while the capacity curve keeps driving up. James argues t=
hat this will eventually lead to grid saturation=E2=80=A6grids will be floo=
ded with cheap solar, to the point it doesn=E2=80=99t even make economical =
sense to buildout more grid connectors.=20
Ultimately, this will lead to more off-grid storage and use of solar. Exces=
s solar will be stored in local batteries, avoiding transmission grid bottl=
enecks. And this cheap, off-grid solar can power processes like fuel produc=
tion and industrial heating that can operate intermittently.
If you are to believe Pueyo and James, the future looks as bright as the su=
n.
(4) =E2=80=98Nuclear clock=E2=80=99 breakthrough paves the way for super-pr=
ecise timekeeping [ https://substack.com/redirect/da8fd1b8-5ca4-4c4f-906a-a=
36c57d2e0e0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
Elizabeth Gibney for Nature
Physicists have demonstrated all the ingredients of a nuclear clock =E2=80=
=94 a device that keeps time by measuring tiny energy shifts inside an atom=
ic nucleus [ https://substack.com/redirect/064f60b8-5576-402e-a70c-aff9b112=
1184?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. =
Such clocks could lead to vast improvements in precision measurements, as w=
ell as new insights into fundamental physics.
Tick-tock on the nuclear clock, but the party don't stop.
A nuclear clock is a timekeeping device that measures time using energy shi=
fts within an atomic nucleus. Recently, physicists have taken a significant=
 step toward developing a nuclear clock by measuring the frequency of energ=
y shifts in thorium-229 nuclei with unprecedented accuracy, 100,000 times g=
reater than previous efforts.
The team used a laser frequency comb to measure the energy shifts in thoriu=
m-229 nuclei embedded in a crystal, synchronizing these shifts with the wor=
ld's most accurate atomic clock. Developing a nuclear clock is important no=
t only because it allows for ultra-precise timekeeping, but also because it=
 could enhance measurements in fundamental physics and help detect phenomen=
a like dark matter.
(Yes, I did put on  Tik Tok by Kesha while writing this. Oh-ooh, oh-ooh, wh=
oa-oh)
(5) Announcing Replit Agent [ https://substack.com/redirect/052a2ebb-69da-4=
ad9-82a7-18aadb59923d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. I gotta admit, with all the love that the AI-native code editor=
 Cursor [ https://substack.com/redirect/1a9333bb-5fd4-40ba-a041-5606b09c1e6=
5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has =
been getting since it announced its $60M raise [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/bb0a518e-871b-46de-8a96-c75040e7ce92?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I=E2=80=99ve been getting a little jeal=
ous of people who know how to code. Cursor is getting rave reviews from dev=
elopers, but its main use case is making actual developers better and faste=
r, not letting non-coders like me build things. To use it to make apps and =
websites, you need to set up a lot of other stuff in addition to writing co=
de, none of which I know how to do.=20
So I was very happy to see our portfolio company, Replit [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/466fafa6-904c-4e5b-85d=
b-82e32236005e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], announce Replit Agent. The ne=
w product lets you build websites and apps simply through prompting. It imp=
orts the right libraries, sets up databases, and deploys for you, in additi=
on to writing the code.=20
I tried it out to build a website for Not Boring, and while I need to tweak=
 it to get the design right and actually import the content I want in there=
, it was able to build me something functional [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/f10f282f-a5c9-40b2-b5b9-87dc821c6b12?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in 10-15 minutes, including a content ma=
nagement system that takes substack links to import my essays and put them =
on the blog page. I=E2=80=99m not going to win any engineering or design aw=
ards, but it=E2=80=99s wild to be able to get something from my brain, into=
 software, and onto the internet within minutes.=20
The gap between idea and execution continues to shrink [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/88cb90f5-e0ea-4059-84e0-2151038fa0f1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. What a time to be alive.
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
Thanks to Percent [ https://substack.com/redirect/4251f75f-f2ce-4de9-a9af-7=
df80bf7f404?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for sponsoring! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

